{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17623544","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17623544"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:12:09+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:12:09+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16869"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16869","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16869"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.57,0.1,0.22,0.02,0.09]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9559"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67400"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9559","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9559"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16869"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52852"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4911"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"9882"},{"type":"tags","id":"9884"},{"type":"tags","id":"10293"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22576"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22580"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67400","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/67400"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the effect of parasympathetic stimulation on vascular smooth muscle?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Muscarinic receptor activation causes vasodilation","Nicotinic receptor activation causes vasodilation","Muscarinic receptor activation causes vasoconstriction","Direct activation of vascular smooth muscle","Release of noradrenaline causing vasodilation"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMuscarinic receptor activation causes vasodilation\u003C/strong\u003E through stimulation of endothelial cells to release nitric oxide. This occurs when acetylcholine is released from parasympathetic nerve terminals.\u003C/p\u003E    \u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E    \u003Cul\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENicotinic receptor activation causes vasodilation\u003C/strong\u003E - Nicotinic receptors are found at autonomic ganglia, not on blood vessels\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMuscarinic receptor activation causes vasoconstriction\u003C/strong\u003E - Muscarinic activation consistently produces vasodilation, not vasoconstriction\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDirect activation of vascular smooth muscle\u003C/strong\u003E - Parasympathetic effects are mediated through endothelial cells, not direct smooth muscle activation\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERelease of noradrenaline causing vasodilation\u003C/strong\u003E - Noradrenaline is a sympathetic, not parasympathetic, neurotransmitter\u003C/li\u003E    \u003C/ul\u003E    \u003Cp\u003EMost blood vessels in the body lack parasympathetic innervation. The exceptions include blood vessels in the brain, heart, and genitalia where parasympathetic nerves can cause vasodilation through nitric oxide release.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Muscarinic receptors in vascular endothelium cause vasodilation through nitric oxide release when activated by acetylcholine.","Parasympathetic innervation is limited primarily to blood vessels in the brain, heart, and genitalia.","Most blood vessels lack direct parasympathetic innervation and are regulated primarily by sympathetic nerves."],"ref